body:
Tested with plugin version 0.0.6:
1. Open IJ, and do File>Open
2. Navigate to `/flutter/examples/hello_world` and hit OK
3. It prompted that Dart support is not enabled, enable it
4. When prompted that "'Pub get' has not been run" hit 'Get dependencies"

Fails with:

```
Working dir: /Users/mit/dev/github/flutter/examples/hello_world
/Users/mit/dev/github/flutter/bin/cache/dart-sdk/bin/pub get
Resolving dependencies...
The Flutter SDK is not available.
Depended on by:
- hello_world 
Process finished with exit code 69
```

Pub should be available there:

```
$ /Users/mit/dev/github/flutter/bin/cache/dart-sdk/bin/pub --version
Pub 1.20.0-dev.10.1
$
```

comment_data.body: cc @devoncarew wonder if this has anything to do with our checked-in project metadata?

This is something we'll need to handle. The way those pubspecs are written (https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/master/examples/hello_world/pubspec.yaml#L5), you can't use `pub get` or `pub upgrade` with them (which IntelliJ is doing). You need to run `flutter packages get` and `flutter packages upgrade`.

Hmmmm....   A few thoughts:
1. Should we train the Dart plugin to ignore pubspecs with `sdk: flutter` set or maybe better still, 
2. should we make the Dart Plugin pub support retargetable so that we can have it call `flutter packages get`? Or, 
3. is there a plan in place to make `pub get` "just work" (a la Dan's shim idea)?
flutter_tools impl of `flutter packages get` here: https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/master/packages/flutter_tools/lib/src/dart/pub.dart#L54
Can we replace the `pubspec.yaml` contributions from the Dart plugin with ones from the Flutter plugin?

That may be tricky as there are actions _and_ inspections we'd want to hijack/retarget.

What about the idea of making `pub get|upgrade` run "the right way" if `sdk: flutter` is specified?  That is, by setting the right environment variables?
Update: after a chat with Alex, I'm going to explore baking some minimal logic into the Dart Plugin proper.

The fix has landed in the Jetbrains repo (https://github.com/JetBrains/intellij-plugins/commit/3cc250319131e6645ffcae26ef4764a745a2cfd1) and will be available with the next Dart plugin release.  I've added a new `waiting-on-release` tag to try and capture this state.  I'm not sure it's quite right.  Essentially, I'd like us to be able to categorize bugs that are "fixed" on our side but are waiting for external factors (like a dart or jetbrains release) so that we can collect them to do the proper updates when they become unblocked.  

@mit-mit : curious if you have a preferred process?

I think that tag approach will be fine.
